2ï¸âƒ£ Bean Scopes


Scope	Meaning
Singleton	- 1 instance per Spring container (default)
Prototype	- New instance every time itâ€™s requested
Request	-     1 instance per HTTP request (web apps)
Session	-     1 instance per HTTP session (web apps)
GlobalSession-	1 instance per global session (portlet apps)



Singleton
    â€¢ Default scope
    â€¢ Only one object is created per Spring container
    â€¢ Same instance is shared everywhere
ğŸ“Œ Used for stateless services
Why Singleton?
    â€¢ Stateless logic
    â€¢ Same service used by many users
ğŸ“Œ Real example:
âœ” PaymentService
âœ” OrderService
âœ” EmailService


Prototype
    â€¢ A new object is created every time you request the bean
    â€¢ Spring does not manage full lifecycle after creation
ğŸ“Œ Used when objects hold state
    â€¢ Why Prototype?
    â€¢ Each request needs a new object
ğŸ“Œ Real example:
âœ” Report generation
âœ” Temporary calculation objects


Request
    â€¢ One bean instance per HTTP request
    â€¢ Valid only in web applications
ğŸ“Œ Used for request-specific data
    â€¢ Why Request?
    â€¢ Data lives only for one HTTP call
ğŸ“Œ Real example:
âœ” Request ID tracking
âœ” API request metadat


Session
    â€¢ One bean instance per HTTP session
    â€¢ Shared across multiple requests in the same session
ğŸ“Œ Used for user-specific data
    â€¢ Why Session?
    â€¢ Data shared across multiple requests of same user
ğŸ“Œ Real example:
âœ” Logged-in user info
âœ” Shopping cart


GlobalSession
    â€¢ One instance per global session
    â€¢ Used in Portlet-based applications (rare now)
ğŸ“Œ Mostly not used in modern Spring Boot apps
    â€¢ Why GlobalSession?
    â€¢ Shared across multiple portlets
ğŸ“Œ Real example:
âœ” Enterprise portal apps (very rare today)


One-Line Memory Trick
Singleton = App, Prototype = Object,
Request = HTTP Call, Session = User, GlobalSession = Portlet


